Plus, we already have a system for education, conferences and work from a distance; systems that are much simpler and more efficient than an entire virtual world where you need to put on a headset, heptic gloves and suits, and still "walk" to school or work.

We need a proper dystopia for a virtual world to become reality in the sense that it's the accepted way to live.

Yo when Paul said I don't like dividends he literally saying I don't like companies paying me to hold their shares. That literally what a dividend is in simple terms. So Paul are you saying no to money ? As an investor?  6:09 then he goes on to say why dividends are highly tax inefficient method of making money by going to the taxes cons of dividends. Alot of what he says is truth, however that not the whole picture.  Cash dividends is taxs in two ways ordinary dividends and qualified dividends. Ordinary dividends get taxed at ordinary income taxs rate (income taxs) but qualified dividends get taxed a lower capital gains rates. Meaning that if you invested companies and hold that share for a period of time. Your dividends are more tax efficient. (Qualified dividends) you can also do research about qualified dividends requirements to get them. One can also get companies that issue stock dividend (scrip dividend): where a company pays their investors by given them more shares of the company they invested in base on a certain requirements amount shares they have of the company. They can either sell those shares,  Ones they pass holding period or hold it,  It's  more taxs efficient. Final point the taxes of dividends depends as well where you filling taxes. Some states in the USA have high or lower state income taxes rates while states like Alaska, Florida, Nevada, south Dakota, Washington, Texas and Wyoming don't taxs dividends or  have personal income taxes or state income taxe. Bottom line I wouldn't say that dividends are highly tax an inefficient however it has it cons  with taxes. Dividends still offer  earning and liquidity (cash) with more consistent's flow of cash that can be used for investments or the investors need or wants while letting some share gather value over time unit he/she decides is time to sell the shares.

I notice your channel focus almost mostly on Ark and Cathy Woods.  I hope you don't mind me saying this.  Cathy is both correct and wrong in very fundamental ways.  She is absolutely right about the world being completely disrupted by tech.  But she is also fundamentally wrong to assume she can predict which company takes most or all, other than Tesla.  I'm willing to bet most of her stock picks will turn out to be the wrong picks.  I'll give you a couple of examples... take Roku... this space is being taken over by the likes of Google TV... being a 3rd party trying to convince TV manufacturers to use your software is tough unless you're Google or Apple or even Amazon... and streaming providers are also going to start developing their own apps and will not want to pay licensing fees of their subscriptions.  Similarly stuff like teledoc,  etc, while the space they are getting in is going to be disrupted but small players like these again, cannot compete with the tech giants when they decide to play in that space... 

Here's my challenge..  instead of focusing on so many stocks... vast majority of which will fail, you can't go wrong with just holding Tesla.  You can from today, open up a Tesla only portfolio and then compare over time with the dozens of other stocks together and see how Tesla alone will outperform them all...

The only company that I think is sure to win in this big tech disruption is Tesla... not to say others won't..  just that who will is quite hard to tell... other than Tesla.

My theory; Well this is what I was saying Saturday. Feel free to decide for yourselves which is more likely;

This analysis requires some assumptions, the most important being that other then TRCH providing a NASDAQ ticker and 100 million in working capital it provides no value moving forward. Not a leap considering TRCH was an oil and gas exploratory company and moving forward MMAT isn't going to be in the oil and gas business. 

Currently Meta has a market cap of 1.489 billion and a share price of 13.95 USD. Meaning they have 106.738 million shares. It's already been announced meta will get a conversion of 1.8 shares in the new ticker MMAT for every 1 share in meta. So from that side we get a total of 192.129 million shares in MMAT. 

Currently (Pre R/S) TRCH has market cap of 785.78 and share price of 4.65 USD. Meaning there is currently 162.016 million shares of TRCH. It's been announced TRCH gets 1 share in MMAT for every 1 share in TRCH. Before converting we need to take into account the reverse split which changes those numbers to 81.008 million shares existing at 9.30 USD. So that's another 81.008 million shares existing in MMAT from the other side. 

In total there will be 273.137 million shares existing for MMAT. In order for MMAT to not even grow but just keep share price from dropping it needs to maintain a total valuation (or put another way market cap) of **2.540 Billion**! Meaning we need to assume that TRCHs gift of a NASDAQ ticker and 100 million dollars will increase METAs value as a company by **1.051billion, or 70.5% in a single weekend!** Suffice to say I'm highly skeptical. 

But wait it gets worse, probably alot of that increase in value was already baked into METAs stock price as 30 days ago the share price was 2.90 USD. Meaning in last month share price has appreciated 481%!

So at the end of the day I have to ask myself; "Has this company really done anything to deserve going from being valued 309.563 million one month ago to being worth 2.54 billion this coming Monday?" My answer is no and hence I expect a big drop off this coming week precipitated by the afforementioned 70% stock dilution happening over this weekend ruining member sentiment. 

I imagine a similar thought process is behind why so many are willing to pay astronomical short borrow fees to continue to short this thing, or even open up new positions. To put them in context the short borrow fee over all last week was over 500 times what it was for another one of my companies, VRTX. 

But hey, maybe I'm just an idiot. I've only been investing 3 months. I already made 5k off of trch swing trading it from 3.50 to 9.00. If my price target is right of it dropping from 9.50 to 3.00 next week I'll make another 5k with my put options. If not I'll still be up 4k so I can live with being wrong. 

Well anywho, good luck!
